======================================================================
KEY DISCOVERY: 21 = 3 × 7 = (x+1) × I(K₃, x) at x=2
======================================================================

  I(K₃, 2) = 7
  I(P₄, 2) = 21 = 3 × 7

  Is 21 = (x+1) · I(K₃, x) at x=2? Let's check:
  (2+1) · I(K₃, 2) = 3 · 7 = 21 ✓

  But this could be a coincidence. Let's check the general formula:
  I(K₃, x) = 1 + 3x (triangle = three vertices, any one is independent)
  (x+1) · I(K₃, x) = (x+1)(1+3x) = 1 + 4x + 3x²
  I(P₄, x) = 1 + 4x + 3x² (path on 5 vertices)

  VERIFIED: I(P₄, x) = (x+1) · I(K₃, x) for ALL x!
  I(P₄, x) = 1 + 4x + 3x²
  (x+1)(1+3x) = 1 + 4x + 3x²  ✓

======================================================================
EUREKA: P₄ AND K₁⊔K₃ ARE I-EQUIVALENT!
======================================================================

  P₄ (path on 4 vertices): 1-2-3-4, connected
  K₁⊔K₃ (vertex + triangle): disconnected

  BOTH have I(G,x) = 1 + 4x + 3x²

  This means: H=21 is forbidden for the SAME reason as H=7!
  I(G,2)=21 requires a graph with independence poly 1+4x+3x²,
  which is I-equivalent to K₁⊔K₃.
  Since K₃ cannot be a component of Ω(T) (THM-201),
  and P₄ cannot be Ω(T) (THM-202),
  BOTH realizations of the polynomial 1+4x+3x² are blocked!

Checking: are P₄ and K₁⊔K₃ the only graphs with I(G,x)=1+4x+3x²?

